{"parse":{"title":"Subjectification (linguistics)","pageid":49285260,"revid":822192047,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Historical_linguistics\" title=\"Historical linguistics\">historical (or diachronic) linguistics</a>, <b>subjectification</b> (also known as <b>subjectivization</b> or <b>subjectivisation</b>) is a <a href=\"/wiki/Language_change\" title=\"Language change\">language change</a> process in which a linguistic expression acquires meanings that convey the speaker's attitude or viewpoint. This is a pragmatic-semantic process, which means that inherent as well as contextual meanings of the given expression are considered. Subjectification is realized in <a href=\"/wiki/Lexical_semantics\" title=\"Lexical semantics\">lexical</a> and grammatical change. It is also of interest to <a href=\"/wiki/Cognitive_linguistics\" title=\"Cognitive linguistics\">cognitive linguistics</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Pragmatics\" title=\"Pragmatics\">pragmatics</a> (cf. <a href=\"/wiki/Ronald_Langacker\" title=\"Ronald Langacker\">Ronald Langacker</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Elizabeth_Traugott\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Elizabeth Traugott\">Elizabeth Traugott</a>).\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Subjectivity_in_language\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Subjectivity in language</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Subjectification_and_intersubjectification\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Subjectification and intersubjectification</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Grammaticalization\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Grammaticalization</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Example\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Example</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Subjectivity_in_language\">Subjectivity in language</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Subjectification_(linguistics)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Subjectivity in language\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>From a <a href=\"/wiki/Synchrony_and_diachrony\" title=\"Synchrony and diachrony\">synchronic</a> perspective, subjectivity can be expressed in language in many ways. First of all, the subject is implied in discourse through any <a href=\"/wiki/Speech_act\" title=\"Speech act\">speech act</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Subjectivity can also be expressed in many grammatical categories, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Grammatical_person\" title=\"Grammatical person\">person</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Valency_(linguistics)\" title=\"Valency (linguistics)\">valence</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Tense-aspect-mood\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Tense-aspect-mood\">tense, aspect, mood</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Evidentiality\" title=\"Evidentiality\">evidentials</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Deixis\" title=\"Deixis\">deictic expressions</a> more generally.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Subjectification_and_intersubjectification\">Subjectification and intersubjectification</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Subjectification_(linguistics)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Subjectification and intersubjectification\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The most prominent research on subjectification to date comes from linguists <a href=\"/wiki/Elizabeth_Traugott\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Elizabeth Traugott\">Elizabeth Traugott</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Ronald_Langacker\" title=\"Ronald Langacker\">Ronald Langacker</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> In Traugott's view, subjectification is a <a href=\"/wiki/Semasiology\" title=\"Semasiology\">semasiological</a> process in which a linguistic element's \"meanings tend to become increasingly based in the speaker's subjective belief state/attitude toward the proposition\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> From Langacker's standpoint, \"an expression's meaning always comprises both subjectively and objectively construed elements, and it is individual conceptual elements within an expression's meaning that, over time, may come to be construed with a greater degree of subjectivity or objectivity\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Traugott also discusses \"intersubjectification\", alternatively calling subjectivity \"(inter)subjectivity\" and subjectification \"(inter)subjectification\". She writes,\n</p>\n<blockquote><p>In my view, subjectification and intersubjectification are the mechanisms by which:</p></blockquote>\n<ul><li><blockquote><p>a. meanings are recruited by the speaker to encode and regulate attitudes and beliefs (subjectification), and,  </p></blockquote></li>\n<li><blockquote><p>b. once subjectified, may be recruited to encode meanings centred on the addressee (intersubjectification).<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_3-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote></li></ul>\n<p>Subjectification occurs in conversation (through <a href=\"/wiki/Speech_act\" title=\"Speech act\">speech acts</a> and has rhetorical aims, and thus implies some degree of intersubjectivity. Intersubjectification does so more blatantly through its \"development of meanings that explicitly reveal incipient design: the designing of utterances for an intended audience...at the discourse level\" and requires subjectification to occur in the first place.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Traugott and Dasher schematize the process of subjectification elsewhere in the following <a href=\"/wiki/Cline_of_instantiation\" title=\"Cline of instantiation\">cline</a>:\n</p>\n<blockquote><p>non-subjective   &gt;   subjective   &gt;   intersubjective<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>   </p></blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Grammaticalization\">Grammaticalization</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Subjectification_(linguistics)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Grammaticalization\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Grammaticalization\" title=\"Grammaticalization\">Grammaticalization</a> is an associated process of language change in which \"lexical items and constructions come in certain linguistic contexts to serve grammatical functions, and once grammaticalized, continue to develop new grammatical functions\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> The processes of subjectification and intersubjectification do not necessarily result in <a href=\"/wiki/Grammaticalization\" title=\"Grammaticalization\">grammaticalization</a>, but there is still a strong correlation between the two.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_3-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> As shown in the cline above, subjectification is theorized to be a unidirectional process; in other words, meanings tend to follow the path from left to right and do not develop in the reverse direction. Grammaticalization is likewise suggested to be a unidirectional phenomenon.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:3_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:3-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Example\">Example</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Subjectification_(linguistics)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Example\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Traugott proposes that the epistemic adverb <i>evidently</i>, which initially meant 'from evidence, clearly' and later developed into a subjective adverb, underwent subjectification:\n</p>\n<ul><li>\"1429 Will Braybroke in Ess.AST 5: 298 <i>Yif thay finde euidently that i haue doon extorcion</i>\n<ul><li>'If they find from evidence that I have performed extortions' (<i>MED</i>)</li></ul></li>\n<li>1443 Pecock Rule 56: <i>More euydently fals \u00fean \u00feis is, \u00feer is no \u00feing</i>\n<ul><li>'There is nothing more clearly false than this' (<i>MED</i>)</li></ul></li>\n<li>1690 Locke, Hum. Und. II. xxix: <i>No Idea, therefore, can be undistinguishable from another ... for from all other, it is evidently different</i> ('evident to all', weak subjective epistemic) (<i>OED</i>)</li>\n<li>20th c.?: <i>He is evidently right</i> (in the meaning 'I conclude that he is right'; strong subjective epistemic inviting the inference of some concession or doubt on speaker's part)\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Subjectification_(linguistics)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Kristeva, Julia (1989). <i>Language--the Unknown: An Initiation into Linguistics</i>. Columbia University Press. p.&#160;11.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Language--the+Unknown%3A+An+Initiation+into+Linguistics&amp;rft.pages=11&amp;rft.pub=Columbia+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.aulast=Kristeva&amp;rft.aufirst=Julia&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASubjectification+%28linguistics%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Talmy, Leonard (1985). \"Lexicalization patterns: Semantic structure in lexical forms\".  In Shopen, Timothy. <i>Language typology and syntactic description: Grammatical categories and the lexicon</i>. <b>3</b>. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. pp.&#160;57\u2013149.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Lexicalization+patterns%3A+Semantic+structure+in+lexical+forms&amp;rft.btitle=Language+typology+and+syntactic+description%3A+Grammatical+categories+and+the+lexicon&amp;rft.place=Cambridge&amp;rft.pages=57-149&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1985&amp;rft.aulast=Talmy&amp;rft.aufirst=Leonard&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASubjectification+%28linguistics%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_3-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_3-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_3-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Traugott, Elizabeth Closs (2010). \"(Inter)subjectivity and (inter)subjectification: A reassessment\".  In Davidse, Kristin. <i>Subjectification, Intersubjectification and Grammaticalization</i>. Berlin/New York: Walter de Gruyter. p.&#160;39.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=%28Inter%29subjectivity+and+%28inter%29subjectification%3A+A+reassessment&amp;rft.btitle=Subjectification%2C+Intersubjectification+and+Grammaticalization&amp;rft.place=Berlin%2FNew+York&amp;rft.pages=39&amp;rft.pub=Walter+de+Gruyter&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.aulast=Traugott&amp;rft.aufirst=Elizabeth+Closs&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASubjectification+%28linguistics%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:2-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:2_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Traugott, Elizabeth Closs (1989). \"On the Rise of Epistemic Meanings in English: An Example of Subjectification in Semantic Change\". <i>Language</i>: 46\u201347. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.2307/414841\">10.2307/414841</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Language&amp;rft.atitle=On+the+Rise+of+Epistemic+Meanings+in+English%3A+An+Example+of+Subjectification+in+Semantic+Change&amp;rft.pages=46-47&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.2307%2F414841&amp;rft.aulast=Traugott&amp;rft.aufirst=Elizabeth+Closs&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASubjectification+%28linguistics%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:1-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Traugott, Elizabeth C.; Dasher, Richard B. (2001). <i>Regularity in Semantic Change</i>. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. p.&#160;31.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Regularity+in+Semantic+Change&amp;rft.place=Cambridge&amp;rft.pages=31&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.aulast=Traugott&amp;rft.aufirst=Elizabeth+C.&amp;rft.au=Dasher%2C+Richard+B.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASubjectification+%28linguistics%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:3-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:3_6-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:3_6-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Hopper, Paul J.; Traugott, Elizabeth C. (2003). <i>Grammaticalization</i>. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. p.&#160;99.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Grammaticalization&amp;rft.place=Cambridge&amp;rft.pages=99&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.aulast=Hopper&amp;rft.aufirst=Paul+J.&amp;rft.au=Traugott%2C+Elizabeth+C.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASubjectification+%28linguistics%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1312\nCached time: 20180908085351\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.112 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.130 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 377/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 8594/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 94/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 6987/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.049/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 2.39 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   97.966      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   97.966      1 -total\n 75.20%   73.667      5 Template:Cite_book\n  7.15%    7.008      1 Template:Cite_journal\n  1.89%    1.850      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:49285260-0!canonical and timestamp 20180908085351 and revision id 822192047\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Historical_linguistics"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Sociolinguistics"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Cline of instantiation"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Cognitive linguistics"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Deixis"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Digital object identifier"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Elizabeth Traugott"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Evidentiality"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Grammatical person"},{"n